04605nam a22005055i 9780773554078DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735540787 a10.1515/97807735540782doi  a(DE-B1597)658025  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPQ6041 7aHIS0450002bisacsh04a860.9/3542231 aFernández-Medina, Nicolás, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLife Embodied :bThe Promise of Vital Force in Spanish Modernity /cNicolás Fernández-Medina. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b20 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v7700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tBlood, Circulation, and the Soul -- tThe Heart of the Matter: Remapping the Body Economy in Juan de Cabriada’s Philosophical Medico-Chemical Letter -- tCartesianism and Its Discontents: Marcelino Boix y Moliner, Martín Martínez, and Diego de Torres Villarroel -- tPolitical Reform and the Order of Nature -- tVitalizing the Medical Revolution in Spain; or, How Sebastián Miguel Guerrero Herreros and Ignacio María Ruiz de Luzuriaga Theorized Life, Death, and Everything in Between -- tThe Subjective Self and the Sublimity of Nature’s Vital Force in Gaspar Melchor de Jovellanos -- tFrom Neo-Hippocratism to the Avant-Garde -- tPursuing the Modern at the End of an Age: Positivist Materialism and the Krausist Ideal in Pedro Mata y Fontanet and Julián Sanz del Río -- tDegeneration, Regeneration, Corporealization: What the Lived Body Can Do According to Miguel de Unamuno, Pío Baroja, and Ramόn Gόmez de la Serna -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concept of vital force – the immanent energy that promotes the processes of life in the body and in nature – has proved a source of endless fascination and controversy. Indeed, the question of what vitalizes the body has haunted humanity since antiquity, and became even more pressing during the Scientific Revolution and beyond. Examining the complexities and theories about vital force in Spanish modernity, Nicolás Fernández-Medina's Life Embodied offers a novel and provocative assessment of the question of bodily life in Spain. Starting with Juan de Cabriada's landmark Carta filosófica, médico-chymica of 1687 and ending with Ramón Gómez de la Serna's avant-gardism of the 1910s, Fernández-Medina incorporates discussions of anatomy, philosophy, science, critical theory, history of medicine, and literary studies to argue that concepts of vital force served as powerful vehicles to interrogate the possibilities and limits of corporeality. Paying close attention to how the body's capabilities were conceived and strategically woven into critiques of modernity, Fernández-Medina engages the work of Miguel Boix y Moliner, Martín Martínez, Diego de Torres Villarroel, Sebastián Guerrero Herreros, Ignacio María Ruiz de Luzuriaga, Gaspar Melchor de Jovellanos, Pedro Mata y Fontanet, Ángela Grassi, Julián Sanz del Río, Miguel de Unamuno, and Pío Baroja, among others. Drawing on extensive research and analysis, Life Embodied breaks new ground as the first book to address the question of vital force in Spanish modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLife in literature. 0aModernism (Literature)zSpain. 0aSpanish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aVital force. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Spain & Portugal.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773554078?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773554078423Coveruhttps://www